\begin_layout Title
Empirical Findings on the Convergence Rates of 1-D Normal Zig-Zag as Variance
 changes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We wish to address the problem of how the rate of convergence varies as
 a function of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 To address this problem in the most simple setting, and hopefully gain
 some insight on the more general case, we first consider a target distribution
 
\begin_inset Formula $d-$
\end_inset

dimensional Normal density with zero mean and 
\begin_inset Formula $d-$
\end_inset

independent coordinates.
 Let us tackle this problem empirically by considering convergence in terms
 of ergodic averages.
 Now in the case of independent coordinates, we can consider the overall
 process as 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 separate processes, with each converging on its own.
 In this respect, it is natural to conjecture that the overall process will
 converge at the rate of the coordinate process with the slowest rate.
 Now in our simple 
\begin_inset Formula $d-$
\end_inset

Normal example, each coordinate only differs in variance.
 This leads us to consider then how do variances affect convergence rates
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 dimensional Normal distributions? Intuitively, densities with greater variance
 are spread apart further and hence our zig-zag process will go further
 away from the origin until it switches.
 So it is reasonable to hypothesize that the time until convergence increases
 as variance increases.
 Thus, this is the first problem we wish to answer empirically.
 For the criteria of convergence and details on the algorithm to compare
 rates of convergence, refer to zigzag_d_plan.lyx file.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Empirical Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We initially consider the case of the predetermined 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon=0.05$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}=0.125,0.25,0.5,...,2.5$
\end_inset

.
 For unity, we fix the number of observations 
\begin_inset Formula $N=10000$
\end_inset

 and compare the distributions of the number of switching points and time
 until convergence for each variance (
\begin_inset Formula $N=10000$
\end_inset

 has been justified empirically to give stable results of mean times after
 repeated experiments).
 
\end_layout

