The table confirms our intuition that the mean time until convergence increases
 as variance increases.
 Another notable feature in this example is that the mean time increases
 linearly for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}\le1$
\end_inset

, but then increases exponentially as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}>1$
\end_inset

.
 The below graph plots this relationship.
 This can also be undrestood in terms of the mean number of switching points
 given in the second row of the table.
 Since the length of each time interval is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, we would expect approximately constant number of switching points where
 the increments in the mean times are linear, and increasing number of switching
 points where the increments are exponential.
 Moreover, the number of switching points is important from a computational
 point of view since the number of iterations we take for the Zig-Zag is
 determined by the number of switching points.
 Hence, it is reasonalbe to measure convergence in terms of computational
 units by the number of switching points before convergence within a predetermin
ed range.
 
